Chinese Stocks in the U.S.: Ctrip.com, New Oriental, PetroChina

-- B y   B e l i n d a   C a o
-- 
2011-10-18T20:57:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-18/chinese-stocks-in-the-u-s-ctrip-com-new-oriental-petrochina.html
The Bank of  New York  Mellon  China 
ADR Index, which tracks American depositary receipts, rose 0.9
percent to 371.47. The New York Stock Exchange Arca China Index
added 1.6 percent to a three-week high of 222.96. The Shanghai
Composite Index declined 2.3 percent to 2,383.49.  The following companies were among the most active Chinese
shares in New York trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses and
prices are as of the close of trading.  Ctrip.com International Ltd. (CTRP)  , China’s biggest
online travel agency, plunged 4 percent to $33.09, a two-week
low. The company will report its third-quarter financial results
Nov. 13. Sales will grow 16 percent to $150 million, according
to the median estimate of seven analysts surveyed by Bloomberg.
That compared with 20 percent growth in revenue in the previous
quarter.  New Oriental Education & Technology Group (EDU)  Inc,
China’s largest private education service provider, fell 12
percent, the most in a year, to $26.39. The company’s sales will
grow 30 percent to 35 percent from a year earlier in the quarter
starting September, after revenue rose 41 percent to $272
million in the three months ended in August, it said in a
statement today.  Oil and natural gas explorers from China,  India  and  South
Korea  are pushing for overseas acquisitions to cut their
dependence on Middle East crude imports, analysts led by  Gordon
Kwan  at Mirae Asset Securities Ltd. wrote in a report today.
Crude futures climbed 2.3 percent to $88.34 a barrel in New
York, the highest settlement price since Sept. 15.  PetroChina Co. (PTR US) the nation’s biggest oil producer,
advanced 3.8 percent, the most since Jan. 31, to a one-month
high of $125.70.  China Petroleum and Chemical Corp. (SNP US), the country’s
biggest refiner, known as Sinopec, gained 2.7 percent, the most
in two weeks, to $94.40.  Cnooc Ltd. (883)  , China’s largest offshore energy
producer, climbed 2.6 percent to $173.72.  To contact the reporter on this story:
